gland":"Kingston upon Thames, Surrey, England","Tower of London, London, England":"London, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Long Ditton, Surrey, England":"Long Ditton, Surrey, England","Richmond, Surrey, England":"Richmond, Surrey, England"},"en":{"about 1479–20 August 1565":"about 1479–20 August 1565","1479–1565":"1479–1565","1478–1569":"1478–1569","1506–1564":"1506–1564","–Male":"Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","1558":"1558","1569":"1569","1479":"1479","1478":"1478","1565":"1565","1564":"1564","about 1479":"about 1479","20 August 1565":"20 August 1565","12 May 1564":"12 May 1564","1506":"1506","1549":"1549","Kingston upon Thames, Surrey, England":"Kingston upon Thames, Surrey, England","Tower of London, London, England":"London, England, United Kingdom","Long Ditton, Surrey, England":"Long Ditton, Surrey, England","Richmond, Surrey, England":"Richmond, Surrey, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Vincent","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English, French, West Indian (mainly Haiti), and Spanish: from the personal name <i>Vincent</i>, Latin <i>Vincentius</i>, a derivative of <i>vincens</i>, genitive <i>vincentis</i>, present participle of <i>vincere</i> ‘to conquer’. The name was borne by a 3rd-century Spanish martyr widely venerated in the Middle Ages and by a 5th-century monk and writer of Lérins, as well as various other early Christian saints.","Irish: the English surname (see 1 above) has been established in the south of Ireland since the 17th century, and has also been adopted as an English equivalent of Gaelic <b>Mac Dhuibhinse</b> ‘son of the dark man of the island’.","History: The surname <i>Vincent</i> of French origin (see 1 above) is listed in the register of Huguenot ancestors recognized by the Huguenot Society of America and also in the similar register of the Huguenot Society of South Carolina."],"variants":[{"name":"St. Vincent","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Leandre, Monique.","French (<b>Saint-Vincent</b>): habitational name from any of several places in various parts of France named Saint-Vincent (from the dedication of their churches to Saint Vincent), or a nickname with the prefix <i>Saint</i> as an (ironic) attachment to the personal name or surname   Vincent  .","History: Vincent Chamereau <i>dit</i> Saint-Vincent from Paris, France, married Marie-Thérèse Auban in Pierrefonds, QC, in 1752."]},{"name":"Venson","meanings":["English: altered form of   Vincent  .","French (Lot-et-Garonne): probably from a vernacular diminutive of the personal name   Vincent  . This surname is very rare in France."]},{"name":"Vince","meanings":["English (East Anglia): from a short form of the personal name   Vincent  .","Hungarian: variant of   Vincze  ."]},{"name":"Vicencio","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Anamaria, Javier, Jesus, Jorge, Juan, Manuel, Mario, Adriana, Alfonso, Amado, Baudelio.","Hispanic (mainly Mexico, Chile, and the Philippines); Portuguese (<b>Vicêncio</b>): from a vernacular form of the Latin personal name <i>Vincentius</i> (see   Vincent  ), a variant of   Vicente  ."]},{"name":"Vincze","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Hungarian Arpad, Laszlo, Aranka, Attila, Bela, Ildiko, Kalman, Lajos, Mihaly, Miklos, Sandor, Zsolt.  Jewish Aron.","Hungarian: from the personal name <i>Vince</i>, Hungarian form of   Vincent  .","Jewish (from Hungary): adoption of the Hungarian surname in 1 above because it has some sounds in common with the original German-based surname."]},{"name":"Sensel","meanings":["South German: probably from a pet form of the Latin personal name <i>Vincens</i> (see   Vincent  ).","German: habitational name from any of the places called Senseln in former East Prussia and Bohemia."]},{"name":"Vicente","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Manuel, Armando, Carlos, Juan, Antonio, Sergio, Enrique, Jorge, Luis, Mario, Adriano, Esteban.  Portuguese Joaquim, Paulo, Aderito, Anabela, Joao, Martinho, Vasco.","Spanish and Portuguese: from the personal name <i>Vicente</i>, an equivalent of   Vincent  ."]},{"name":"Vincelette","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Aime, Alphonse, Fernand, Normand.","Americanized form of French <b>Vincelet</b>: derivative of   Vincent  . It reflects the Canadian and American French practice of sounding the final <i>-t</i>."]},{"name":"Vincenti","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Aldo, Angelo, Attilio, Carlo, Dante, Gino, Marco, Querino, Vito.","Italian: patronymic or plural form of the personal name <i>Vincente</i> (see   Vincent  ). This surname is also found in Corsica and southern France."]},{"name":"Vincenzo","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Silvio, Angelo, Emilio, Fortunato, Mario.","Italian: from the personal name <i>Vincenzo</i>, a cognate of<i>Vincente</i> (see   Vincent  )."]}]},{"name":"Aylward","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from a Middle English personal name, <i>Ailward</i>, Old English <i>Æthelweard</i>, composed of elements meaning ‘noble’ + ‘guardian’. This English name has been established in Ireland since at least the 16th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Alward","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Alward</i>, <i>Elward</i>, a shortened form of several Old English names, such as <i>Ælfweard</i> (Middle English <i>Alfward</i>), <i>Ealdweard</i>, and (especially in Devon) <i>Æthelweard</i>, which survives as Middle English   Aylward  , <i>Alward</i>, and probably <i>Elward</i>.","North German: variant of   Alwardt   and, in North America, (also) an altered form of this."]},{"name":"Elward","meanings":["English (Glamorgan): variant of   Aylward   or   Alward  ."]}]},{"name":"David","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical name, borne by the greatest of all the kings of Israel, whose history is recounted with great vividness in the first and second books of Samuel and elsewhere. As a boy he killed the giant Philistine Goliath with his slingshot. As king of Judah, and later of all Israel, he expanded the power of the Israelites and established the security of their kingdom. He was also noted as a poet, many of the Psalms being attributed to him. The Hebrew derivation of the name is uncertain; it is said by some to represent a nursery word meaning ‘darling’. It is a very popular Jewish name, but is almost equally common among Gentiles in the English-speaking world. It is particularly common in Wales and Scotland, having been borne by the patron saint of Wales (  see  Dewi   ) and by two medieval kings of Scotland."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":70,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":79,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"David Vincent Aylward was born about 1479, in Long Ditton, Surrey, England as the son of John Vincent and Ann Hill. He had at least 1 daughter with Elizabeth Spencer Hodnot. He died on 20 A